1Ô∏è‚É£ var (Java 10)
What it is
var enables local variable type inference.

The compiler infers the type from the initializer.

Rules (very important)
‚úÖ Only for local variables

‚ùå Cannot be used for:

fields

method parameters

return types

‚ùå Must be initialized immediately

Example
var message = "Hello, Java 10!";   // inferred as String
var count = 10;                   // inferred as int
‚ùå Invalid:

var x;            // no initializer
var y = null;     // cannot infer type
Key point
var is not dynamic typing ‚Äî Java is still statically typed.

2Ô∏è‚É£ yield (Java 14)
What it is
yield is used inside a switch expression to return a value.

It ‚Äúyields‚Äù a value from a switch block.

Why it was needed
Old switch:

worked as a statement

required break

error-prone

New switch:

works as an expression

returns a value

Example
int result = switch (day) {
    case MONDAY, TUESDAY -> 1;
    case FRIDAY -> {
        yield 5;
    }
    default -> 0;
};
Key rule
yield is used only inside switch expressions

It is not a loop keyword (unlike in some other languages)

3Ô∏è‚É£ record (Java 16)
What it is
A record is a special class for immutable data.

It automatically generates boilerplate code.

What Java generates for you
constructor

getters

equals()

hashCode()

toString()

Example
public record Person(String name, int age) {}
Equivalent to writing ~50 lines manually.

Usage
Person p = new Person("Vishnu", 22);
System.out.println(p.name()); // getter
Rules
Records are final

Fields are private final

Best for DTOs / data holders

4Ô∏è‚É£ sealed, permits (Java 17)
What they are
Used to restrict inheritance.

You control which classes can extend a class.

Example
public sealed class Shape
        permits Circle, Rectangle {
}
final class Circle extends Shape {}
final class Rectangle extends Shape {}
Why this exists
Prevent uncontrolled inheritance

Useful for domain models

Helps the compiler with exhaustiveness checks (especially with switch)

Rules
Permitted subclasses must be:

final

sealed

or non-sealed

5Ô∏è‚É£ Java Module System keywords (Java 9)
These keywords belong to JPMS (Java Platform Module System).

module
Defines a module

module com.example.app {
    requires java.sql;
}
requires
Declares dependency on another module

requires java.logging;
requires transitive
Dependency is passed to dependent modules

requires transitive java.sql;
exports
Makes a package accessible to other modules

exports com.example.util;
exports ‚Ä¶ to
Exports only to specific modules

exports com.example.internal to com.friend.module;
open
Opens entire module for reflection

open module my.module {
}
opens
Opens a package for reflection

opens com.example.model;
uses
Declares usage of a service

uses com.example.Service;
provides ‚Ä¶ with
Provides implementation of a service

provides com.example.Service
    with com.example.ServiceImpl;
Why modules matter
Strong encapsulation

Better dependency management

Faster startup

Smaller runtime images

6Ô∏è‚É£ _ (underscore)
What happened
Earlier Java versions allowed _ as an identifier

From Java 9 ‚Üí reserved

Now cannot be used as a variable name

‚ùå Invalid:

int _ = 10;
Reason
Reserved for potential future language features.

üìå Summary Table (quick revision)
Keyword	Java Version	Purpose
var	10	Local type inference
yield	14	Return value from switch expression
record	16	Immutable data class
sealed	17	Restrict inheritance
permits	17	Allowed subclasses
module	9	Define module
requires	9	Module dependency
exports	9	Expose package
_	9+	Reserved identifier